The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, June 01, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 Bajaj Tempo Ltd, a Firodia enterprise, has posted a higher net profit at Rs 44.21 crore for 2003-04 against Rs 32.17 crore in 2002-03. The board has recommended a 70 per cent dividend for the year ended March 31, 2004, the company said in a statement. Net sales rose to Rs 944.21 crore from Rs 700.03 crore in the previous year, it said.																								 PeopleSoft India has extended an existing alliance with Convansys Corporation of the US to include consulting and implementation services to manufacturing and healthcare segment clients in India. 																								 Ati Technologies Inc, a three-dimensional graphics and digital media silicon solutions provider, has launched its operations in India and appointed Advent Media-Tech Pvt Ltd as its sales representative for personal computers, notebooks and workstation products.																								 Hindustan Colas Ltd (Hincol), a joint venture of Hindustan Petroleum Corporation Ltd and Colas SA, France, has set up a new plant at Visakhapatnam to manufacture value-added bitumen-based products. The new plant would also cater to Orissa and Chhattisgarh.																								 Maxtor, a leading hard disk supplier, has tied up with Almasa, an European distributor, for marketing its products in India. Almasa is Maxtors fourth distributor in the country, besides Cyberstar, Ingram Micro and Esys.																								 DHL has launched its next-generation wireless scanners at an investment of five lakh euro for its on-the-go customer service agents to keep an eye on shipments. These scanners equip the DHL field force with the up-to-the-minute shipment tracking information even from customer locations, a DHL release said.																								 Bongaigaon Refinery and Petrochemicals Limited (BRPL) has recorded the highest- ever sales turnover of Rs 2,848.67 crore, recording a 53.03 per cent increase. The company has posted a net profit of Rs 303.74 crore for the year, registering a quantum leap of 70.22 per cent over the previous year, a company release said.																								 Avesthagen, a biotechnology firm, has received a government grant of Rs 2.75 crore to help it produce a fatty acid by 2006, which will be used in nutritional food. The grant has been given by the Council of Scientific and Industrial Research (CSIR) under the new millennium initiative for technology leadership, a company statement said.																								 Hindustan Lever Ltd (HLL) has unveiled Perfect Radiance, a range of 12 skincare solutions from Fair amp; Lovely. Perfect Radiance contains international formulations from Unilevers global skin technology centre, HLL said in a release. ADVERTISEMENT
